you can try to capture the original spirit of the joke - for example, if the original joke was a silly pun, you can figure out another pun with a similar level of silliness to get the general idea across

again again you can feel how you want about this i'm not saying the ability to shorthand is automatically good or bad i'm just saying it's a fact of the medium of fanfiction that you get to skip explaining some things because you can assume your reader knows it already

the fact that you can assume the reader knows the source material lets you shorthand a lot of character dynamics, themes, and concepts you would otherwise have to explain or demonstrate in original fiction

again i'm not arguing that fanfic is inherently Good Art bc of this or anything but i do think aspects of it are widely misunderstood bc setting and characters are really just a surface level idea of what gets taken from canon

now you can make an argument as to whether you feel this dependence on context is a good thing, but either way it is kind of an inherent feature of the medium and it is i think a core part of the appeal of reading and writing it

like "why is this a fanfic if you've completely changed the setting" it is inherently funnier to make fire emblem characters work in a grocery store than it is to make up wholly new characters to put in the same setting. there is a context that changes the framing, inherently

even if it changes most or all of the basic facts, a good fanfic will still be conscious of your expectations based on the fact that it is a fanfic....and it will use those expectations accordingly. idk the fact that it depends on context is an interesting facet of fic imo

a lot of those aus would not stand on their own as original works even if they are very different from the source material because they'll still assume the reader will have certain understandings and expectations about characters & their dynamics based on the source material

not all fanfic is good or does this well but i do feel like...when you do an au where characters all have different jobs and lives, part of the appeal is seeing the adaptation of everyone's roles into a different setting. the contrast with the original work is a big part of it
